On Wednesday, May 18, the Czech government approved a change in the conditions for paying humanitarian aid to Ukrainian refugees.
Today, all arriving Ukrainian refugees are entitled to a first aid payment of 5,000 CZK, without any additional conditions (only a temporary protection visa is required).
To receive the same amount for the next five months, the applicant must prove his difficult financial situation - being considered unemployed, not having any property in the Czech Republic, etc.
The Ministry of Labor decided to change this practice as follows:
1Ô∏è‚É£ The first payment of assistance will no longer be unconditional.
If a refugee is provided with free housing, daily multiple meals, and hygiene items, he will not be able to claim the 5,000 kroons payment.
The authorities will begin to believe that basic assistance was provided in kind (housing, food, and hygiene products), which means that the purpose of humanitarian aid has been fulfilled and there is no need to pay money.
This event is designed to solve the problem of Roma refugees from Ukraine.
Many of them come to the Czech Republic only for financial assistance.
2Ô∏è‚É£ The right to receive cash payments of the second, third, fourth, fifth and sixth assistance, as before, will be reserved for only those refugees who prove immediate need (lack of work, etc.).
However, two more conditions will be added:
üìå as in the first point, only those Ukrainians who were not provided with free housing, daily multiple meals, and hygiene supplies will be able to receive cash assistance;
üìå the applicant must actually reside in the Czech Republic.
This is necessary to stop the practice of &quot;aid tourism&quot;, when a refugee lives in one country and comes to the Czech Republic for a few days solely for money.
According to the law, every foreigner is obliged to inform the Ministry of Internal Affairs of a change of residence within three working days after moving.
If the address on the application for benefits does not match the address listed in the Ministry of Internal Affairs database, the applicant will be asked to provide evidence that she actually lives in the Czech Republic.
Otherwise, the payment of assistance will be denied.
To date, the Czech Republic has spent 2.626 billion CZK on humanitarian aid.
