Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky believes that relations between Berlin and Kyiv are developing &quot;wave-like&quot; against the backdrop of Russian aggression - they have &quot;ups and downs.&quot;
He voiced this position in an interview with the German weekly magazine Der Spiegel, published on Thursday, February 9.
&quot;By nature, I am a fast person.
&quot;Others are acting more slowly, which may also be related to their bureaucracy,&quot; Zelenskyy noted, adding that in a war situation, Ukraine does not have weeks and months, and people&#39;s lives depend on the development of the situation every moment.
Air defense revival
The President of Ukraine noted that at a certain stage, Germany&#39;s &quot;conservative attitude&quot; changed and he received the support of Chancellor Olaf Scholz.
&quot;Then I finally received support from Steinmeier (President of Germany Frank-Walter Steinmeier - Ed.), with whom I had previously had difficulties, especially because of the so-called &quot;Steinmeier formula,&quot; Zelensky noted.
He emphasized that &quot;good work&quot; had been done, which allowed for a change in relations.
&quot;We received the IRIS-T air defense systems, for which I am very grateful to Germany.
&quot;They saved many lives,&quot; the President of Ukraine noted.
According to Zelensky, Berlin has managed to increase the pace of production of these systems.
Previously, Germany promised to transfer three more IRIS-T complexes to Ukraine in 2023.
Braking with tanks
However, the debate surrounding the supply of Leopard battle tanks to Kyiv has returned relations with Germany &quot;into a difficult phase,&quot; the Ukrainian president noted.
He called the discussions on this issue &quot;emotional and complex.&quot;
&quot;I have to force him (Scholz - Ed.) to help Ukraine and constantly convince him that this help is needed not by us, but by the Europeans,&quot; Zelensky explained.
