the number of victims reached 23 thousand - DW - 11.02.2023
Earthquakes in Turkey and Syria have killed more than 23,000 people.
According to the Turkish Ministry of Health, as of Saturday morning, February 11, the number of victims in this country alone exceeded 20.6 thousand, and more than 80 thousand people were injured.
Read also: Turkey will continue to be shaken.
How dangerous are aftershocks?
Despite the fact that due to sub-zero temperatures in the region, the hope of saving people is becoming less and less, rescue operations continue.
Thus, 102 hours after the earthquake in southern Turkey, a family of six was rescued from the rubble, according to the state-run Anadolu news agency.
A total of 166,000 Turkish and foreign rescuers, police, medics and volunteers are involved in the rescue efforts.
Of these, more than eight thousand rescuers are from 61 countries.
A total of 97 countries have sent aid to Turkey, the Turkish Foreign Ministry said.
White Helmets in Syria criticize UN for lack of aid
According to estimates by the United Nations (UN), the earthquake left about 5.4 million people homeless.
Read also: What is known about the most destructive earthquakes in human history
In Turkey, almost 171,000 tents have been set up in the region affected by the earthquakes.
According to official data, more than one and a half million blankets were delivered to the disaster site.
Meanwhile, in Syria, representatives of the non-governmental organization &quot;White Helmets&quot;, which carries out rescue missions in rebel-controlled regions, complain that they lack support.
On February 10, a White Helmets representative said that only two small international teams of volunteers, who do not have rescue equipment, had arrived in the region to provide assistance.
In addition, according to him, no humanitarian aid from the UN is being received in the region.
Meanwhile, the London-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights, which reports on events in rebel-held northern Syria, said that a UN aid shipment had arrived in the region the day before, but it lacked shelter tents and rubble-clearing equipment.
About three thousand White Helmets volunteers are involved in rescue operations in northern Syria.
According to their data, the group was able to save almost three thousand people.
The bodies of about two thousand people have been found, and more than 3,300 people are considered dead.
More than 10,000 were injured.
The most powerful earthquake since 1939
Early in the morning of February 6, a powerful earthquake with a magnitude of 7.8 struck southeastern Turkey and northern Syria.
This earthquake was the most powerful in almost a century of observations.
The last time Turkey experienced earthquakes of this magnitude was in 1939, when about 33,000 people died.
In less than 12 hours, a second powerful earthquake of magnitude 7.5 shook southeastern Turkey, which was also felt in Syria and Lebanon.
