Cyprus holds decisive round of presidential elections - DW - 02/12/2023
The second, decisive round of presidential elections is taking place in the Republic of Cyprus on Sunday, February 12.
It included the country&#39;s former Foreign Minister Nikos Christodoulides and the former Permanent Representative of Cyprus to the UN Andreas Mavroyiannis.
Conservative politician Christodoulides received 32 percent of the vote in the first round, while his rival in the second round, Mavroyiannis, who is supported by left-wing forces, received 29.6 percent, ahead of the leader of the ruling Democratic Union (DISY) party, Averof Neophyta.
The DISY party, after the defeat of its candidate in the first round, was unable to decide who to support, which made the results of the decisive vote even more unpredictable, notes the AFP agency.
The President of the Republic of Cyprus, which has been a member of the European Union since 2004, is elected by universal suffrage.
He forms and heads the country&#39;s government.
The winner of the current election will serve as head of state for five years and will become the eighth president of Cyprus.
Cyprus was divided into two parts in 1974 as a result of a coup supported by the Greek junta and the subsequent intervention of the Turkish army.
In 1983, the northern sector of the island occupied by the Turks declared itself the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus, which was recognized only by Ankara.
The last negotiations on the attempted reunification of Cyprus ended without results in 2017.
Only Greek Cypriots - about 560 thousand people - are participating in the elections.
Residents of the unrecognized Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus do not vote for them.
