Greek Foreign Minister visits Turkey - DW - 02/12/2023
Earthquakes in the border regions of Turkey and Syria have led to cautious diplomatic rapprochement between Turkey and Greece - long-standing opponents, dpa wrote on Sunday, February 12.
On the same day, the Foreign Ministers of the two countries, Nikos Dendias and Mevlut Cavusoglu, held a surprise meeting, at which, as recorded by Greek television cameras, they even hugged.
Greece was one of the first to help Ankara
Cavusoglu thanked Dendias for Greece being one of the first countries to provide immediate assistance to Turkey after the natural disaster.
He added that both states will try to resume dialogue and resolve their problems.
&quot;Greece&#39;s assistance to the Turkish people does not end there,&quot; the Greek Foreign Minister emphasized.
According to him, Athens &quot;will do everything&quot; - bilaterally, as well as within the EU - to help Turkey.
Dendias became the first EU foreign minister to visit the disaster zone.
Several Greek rescue teams are working in the Antakya and Hatay regions.
A new beginning in bilateral relations?
Political observers and columnists in the Greek press have been expressing hope for several days that the aid provided by Athens to Ankara could be a new beginning in relations between the two countries.
Both NATO members had already shown solidarity with each other during the severe earthquakes in Turkey and Greece in 1999.
This aid, known as &quot;earthquake diplomacy,&quot; helped achieve some de-escalation at the time.
Conflict over islands
Athens and Ankara have been arguing for decades over sovereign rights in the Aegean Sea and the eastern Mediterranean.
Ankara questions Greece&#39;s sovereignty over a number of islands in the eastern Aegean Sea - Rhodes, Lesbos, Samos and Kos.
Greece is allegedly violating international treaties by maintaining a military presence there.
Athens justifies the deployment of troops on the islands by the threat of numerous landing craft on the Turkish west coast and the right of every state to self-defense.
Read also: Are Greece and Turkey on the brink of armed conflict?
Turkey reinforces its claims almost daily with fighter jet flights over the Greek islands.
And in recent months, the country&#39;s leader Erdogan has repeatedly threatened to invade the Greek islands.
Ankara&#39;s warming relations with Armenia
Amid the tragedy caused by the earthquakes, there is also a warming of relations between Turkey and Armenia.
Ankara opened a crossing closed for over 30 years, through which trucks carrying humanitarian aid from Armenia for victims of the disaster passed.
In addition, Armenia announced the dispatch of two rescue teams to Turkey and Syria after the earthquake that occurred on February 6 and claimed the lives of more than 33,000 people.
Relations between Ankara and Yerevan are tense for historical reasons - about 1.5 million Armenians were victims of systematic killings in the Ottoman Empire during World War I.
As the successor state of the Ottoman Empire, Turkey admits that it exterminated several hundred thousand Armenians, but refuses to define it as genocide.
Meanwhile, the Armenian genocide was condemned, in particular, by the United States, Germany, and France.
The land border between Turkey and Armenia was closed in 1993.
Against the backdrop of the conflict in Nagorno-Karabakh and Turkey&#39;s support for Azerbaijan, the situation only became more complicated.
