President Maia Sandu&#39;s briefing took place a week after Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said that his country had intercepted Russian intelligence plans to destroy Moldova, which was later confirmed by Moldovan intelligence officials.
&quot;The plan for the next period involves the involvement of saboteurs with military training, camouflaged in civilian clothes, who will resort to forceful actions, attack some state buildings and even take hostages,&quot; Sandu told reporters at a briefing.
&quot;The goal of these actions is to overthrow the constitutional order, to change the legitimate government of Chisinau to an illegitimate one,&quot; Sandu said, &quot;which would place our country at the disposal of Russia and stop the process of European integration.&quot;
She promised: &quot;The Kremlin&#39;s attempts to bring violence to our country will not succeed.&quot;
Russian officials did not respond to Sandu&#39;s statements.
Since Russia invaded Ukraine, Moldova, a former Soviet republic with a population of about 2.6 million people, has sought to forge closer relations with its Western partners.
In June last year, it received candidate status for the European Union, on the same day as Ukraine.
Sandu said that between October and December, Moldovan police and the Intelligence and Security Service (SIS) intervened in &quot;several cases of organized criminal elements and stopped attempts at violence.&quot;
Moldova, which is not a NATO member, has faced a number of challenges over the past year.
These include a serious energy crisis after Moscow sharply cut gas supplies; soaring inflation; and several incidents in recent months involving missiles that crossed the airspace and debris that was found in its territory.
Moldovan authorities confirmed that another missile from the Ukraine war entered its airspace on Friday.
Sandu stated that Russia wanted to use Moldova in a war against Ukraine and that the information obtained by the intelligence services contained what she called instructions on the rules of entry into Moldova for citizens of Russia, Belarus, Serbia, and Montenegro.
&quot;I assure you that state institutions are working to prevent these challenges and keep the situation under control,&quot; Sandu said.
She said that the Moldovan parliament should adopt bills to provide the Intelligence and Security Service, as well as the Prosecutor&#39;s Office, with &quot;the necessary tools to more effectively combat risks to the country&#39;s security.&quot;
The president added that the plan would &quot;rely on several internal forces, but especially criminal groups,&quot; and went on to name two Moldovan oligarchs, Ilan Shor and Volodymyr Plahotniuc, both of whom are currently in exile.
Last year, the US and the UK imposed sanctions on both men.
Last fall, a series of mass anti-government protests organized by the populist, Russia-friendly Shor party also rocked Moldova amid an energy crisis.
The president&#39;s press briefing on Monday came after Moldovan Prime Minister Natalia Gavrilita resigned on Friday.
On the same day, Sandu appointed her defense and security advisor, pro-Western economist Dorin Receanu, as Gavrilita&#39;s successor.
