How attitudes towards Ukrainians have changed and why the EU does not pay for refugees - analysis from an expert
Poland and the Czech Republic do not receive refugee aid from the EU - this is the most discussed topic at meetings between the presidents of these two countries.
Andrzej Duda visited the Czech Republic at the invitation of Milo≈° Zeman.
The President of the Czech Republic noted that since the beginning of the war in Ukraine, Poland has become the main defender of European values and has taken on the task of solving many problems.
It provided shelter to 2 million Ukrainians, helped with housing, and provided financial assistance.
Approximately 500,000 arrived in the Czech Republic.
Ukrainians will never forget such powerful support from their neighbors ‚Äì Poland and the Czech Republic ‚Äì and will be tirelessly grateful!
How Poland is experiencing the unexpected wave of refugees and the financial burden, the ProUkrainian editorial office asked Yaroslav Kot, coordinator and translator of the Refugee Center in Lublin.
He is also the founder of the Institute for Global and Regional Analytics, which has offices not only in Poland, but also in Canada, Ukraine, and Kazakhstan.
How Poland helps Ukrainians
The Czech Republic accepted up to half a million Ukrainians, and this had a significant impact on the lives of Czechs.
There are long queues in the labor governments, significant price increases in the stores.
What is happening in Poland, where there are millions of Ukrainian refugees?
The Polish government organized itself exceptionally quickly and began providing assistance when hostilities began.
This was foreseen.
In Poland, they have been saying for the past few months that there will be such a huge problem.
Even in Ukraine, there was less preparation for what was to happen, while in Poland, there was active preparation.
For example, in the border regions of Poland and Ukraine, even before the war began, there were already certain plans for where refugees from Ukraine would be placed.
In Ukraine, they didn&#39;t even think that something like this could happen.
I heard people smiling about Poland&#39;s fear of refugees.
But it was very deliberate: to prepare for all these events even before the war began.
I would like to note that extremely large funds were allocated from regional and state budgets to help Ukrainians fleeing the bombings and the Russian aggressor.
First of all, assistance with logistics - moving around Poland.
There are special trains from Ukraine to Poland, including medical trains for the wounded and sick.
These are planes that travel within Poland between cities, as well as charter flights to EU countries.
I have had experience working with such flights to Portugal, France, Romania and Spain from Lublin.
Although the city of Lublin is similar in size to Lutsk, not a city of a million, as some might think.
The transport issue remains extremely important.
In Poland, travel fees for Ukrainians have been canceled.
They can travel for free on trains and public transport.
In addition, Poland has reached an agreement with German carriers, which have organized free trains to Germany from several Polish cities.
That is, refugees have the opportunity to travel free of charge to the places where they plan to stay.
The second issue is the accommodation of refugees in facilities provided by local governments.
Mostly these are small indoor school stadiums, complexes where temporary halls with beds are set up.
Free meals and free medical first aid are organized there.
Refugees have the opportunity to rest and stay for a few days, and already there, they are looking for opportunities to move to more comfortable conditions.
The large cities of Warsaw, Gdansk, and Wroclaw have become very active, where entire Ukrainian neighborhoods have now been created.
The example of Warsaw is generally unique in the sense that they managed to get the Russian embassy to take back the facilities that were abandoned by the residents of this embassy.
Large residential complexes stood in a neglected state for decades, but the Russians did not let anyone in.
The Polish local government nationalized it, so to speak.
It was taken for the benefit of Ukrainians, Ukrainian families will live there.
These are apartment buildings that can accommodate 200-300 families at once.
Water and electricity will be supplied there, and they will be insulated.
In a week or two, refugees from Ukraine could already be living there.
The third aspect is social assistance.
After February 24, Poland took a unique step - the Sejm adopted, and the Senate approved, a law on refugees from Ukraine.
According to it, Ukrainian citizens have the right to legally reside in Poland for 18 months.
They have the right to work without a work permit, which is mandatory in all European Union countries.
This law provides for medical care.
In addition, there is a private foundation that has allocated ten million zlotys for free medical assistance to Ukrainians.
You just need to write an SMS and receive a code on your phone.
And in terms of 5 thousand hryvnias, you can get medicine for free in Poland.
Social assistance is three hundred zlotys, which is provided irrevocably to every refugee from Ukraine, regardless of age.
Various foundations are common, including Caritas and the Red Cross, which provide packages with food, chemicals, and clothing.
As the Poles say: &quot;Niespotykana skala&quot;.
That is, &quot;an event that has no analogues.&quot;
Such a huge openness.
This is a huge expense for the Polish state.
The European Union has not allocated a single euro to Poland to date.
In fact, this is an extremely large blow to the Polish budget.
What is the biggest problem in the adaptation of Ukrainians in Poland?
Language problem.
The questions start with clinics, where Ukrainians cannot manage without an interpreter.
Often with complex problems and illnesses.
The second problem is schools where students, especially in the upper grades, also struggle at first and cannot understand the terminology.
I note that Ukrainian children often arrive with a level of knowledge much higher than in the corresponding class.
This often surprises Polish teachers.
Children not only have good English skills, but their overall level is higher than the grade they are in.
This is also interesting.
That is, the Ukrainian education system is good.
And, in fact, children study well in Ukraine, if they are valued so highly here.
Of course, language is important during employment.
Unfortunately, it is much more difficult for an employee who worked as a doctor, accountant, or lawyer in Ukraine to master this job here.
As a lawyer or an accountant, I don&#39;t know of any such cases.
Doctors are now appearing in certain locations, in particular in Lublin, the company has created its own small clinic with Ukrainian doctors.
This is a Polish initiative where Ukrainian doctors have the opportunity to accept the same Ukrainians on legal grounds.
The language barrier is often the reason that prompts families to return home after a few weeks of being here.
There are many such cases.
In the last few weeks, we have had a whole wave of refugees who fled in the first weeks of the war, now they are returning.
These are Transcarpathia and the western regions of Ukraine, where there are no such active military operations.
They did not settle here, they did not find work.
Where they live, the conditions do not meet their needs and accordingly they would be more comfortable returning home.
This is also one of the problems that has arisen in recent weeks.
How attitudes towards Ukrainians have changed
According to the Ukrainian ambassador to the Czech Republic, significant changes have occurred.
If previously Czech society considered Ukrainians exclusively as labor migrants, now it is proud of the resilience of Ukrainians who defend their country.
How do Poles feel about millions of Ukrainian refugees?
There is a similar situation in Poland.
Here, all television channels often quote the statement of Polish President Lech Kaczynski, who tragically died in Smolensk.
When the events of Russia&#39;s attack on Georgia took place, he was in Tbilisi, along with President Yushchenko and other heads of state.
There he said a significant phrase that Russian aggression will definitely not stop at Georgia, and then maybe Ukraine.
Then there could be the Baltic countries, and it could even reach Poland.
That is, as if he had foreseen it.
In fact, Ukrainians are now defending Poland with their blood, their devotion, and their heroic deeds.
Poland and Poles appreciate this, which is why they open their homes and help Ukrainian refugees so selflessly.
They see a threat in Poland.
Despite the fact that Poland is in NATO, despite the fact that there are American military bases here, there is a certain fear that war could also knock on our door.
That&#39;s why the attitude changed to a positive one.
The Ukrainian flag, the Ukrainian anthem are now in Poland not a ‚Äúsong of nationalists‚Äù or some enemies.
Of course, there are still small groups among the population who have not changed their views, they exist in every country.
But, fortunately, the majority of citizens in society now think completely differently about Ukrainians than before.
The statement about nationalists in Ukraine is ridiculous.
Putin and other Russian politicians constantly claim that there are nationalists in Ukraine who need to be eliminated.
This is simply perceived with laughter in Poland, because these so-called ‚Äúnationalists‚Äù turned out to be completely different people, they have no political overtones.
And this is certainly impressive, because this direct contact influenced the change in public opinion of those segments of society that still had doubts about some historical issues.
Now it turned out that these doubts were not confirmed.
Ukrainians are heroes.
When Poles start to think that there might be a war, they immediately begin to understand that they would not be able to resist and give their lives as is happening now in Ukraine.
People here are constantly talking about people from Mariupol, Bucha, and other Ukrainian cities.
How Poland perceives Russian threats
Ukraine believes in victory, but is preparing for the worst-case scenario, because a terrible war is ongoing.
But now Poland and the Czech Republic, which have already received threats, are seriously considering their own security.
Russia threatens to use nuclear weapons as punishment for supporting Ukraine.
How are the authorities and society in Poland reacting?
If you want peace, prepare for war.
